Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in the course of amending the Criminal Procedure Code, rejected an attempt to repeal an article condemning the leader of the opposition, Yulia Timoshenko.
An amendment that would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years ' imprisonment for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unfavourable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will hear Timoshenko ' s appeal in December.
Timoshenko claims that the verdict is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister had been convicted, had been supported by 147 members of Parliament.
Ratification would require 226 votes.
