Nutrition of children suffering from obesity: No breakfast or sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9 per cent of schoolchildren are overweight, 5 per cent are obese.
According to the latest study, children suffering from obesity usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and the patterns of behaviour that accompany the human being for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage appears almost twice as frequently on the tables of children suffering from obesity as in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19 percent of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner prior to the poll on an educational event called Obesity is not an accident.
Moreover, the families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports, but this is true of most families in modern schools - only 15 per cent of the children said that their parents found time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of the last school year and was attended by nearly 900 primary school students throughout Bohemia.
Obesity was not an accident for the second year in a row, with the support of Všeobecná zdravotní pojiškovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Good nutrition and sufficient sport are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of those interviewed said that they eat five meals a day, on the basis of a luncheon, luncheon, snack, snack, and this is one of the essential conditions for proper nutrition," says one of the conclusions of the study.
No lunch and sausage at night.
Experts warn that even relative details, such as the constant time of family breakfast, are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families eat breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast separately.
The worst discovery is that every tenth family has no breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study showed that roasted food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly engage in sports, this figure drops by more than half - to 15 per cent - when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to prepare their own menus based on the products offered and on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Their favorite food includes a large quantity of flour, meat, and sweet food.
"The great popularity of sweet cool drinks is of particular concern," says the final part of the study.
As the main dining meal, the pasta defeated the bird with a slight overweight.
However, children showed little interest in beans, fish and vegetables.
The Struggle for a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children are prepared to change their eating habits, provided that they are provided with relevant information.
"A large number of participants in the study team have demonstrated a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they fill out the questionnaire after the lecture Obesity is not an accident," the outcome of the project states.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet cool drinks - more children preferred just water to them.
In addition, as the main dish, children more frequently marked birds and fish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and pastries.
