V Need for Speed: The escape takes place in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk became a routine morning trip to work due to a series of totally inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambition was to some extent satisfied, but it doesn't matter, because no one clearly wanted to do any extra work.
Before the new version with the sub-heading "Escape," there were great hopes.
It was expected to move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; demonstration versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the race games genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main hero gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, the result is a lot different than what we expected.
The game is a rather good arcade race, but the general impression is that there are several unnecessary errors that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So it's not really a mistake, it's an unexplained laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You become part of a story whose main hero, Jack, solves some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race goes on its own route, and the individual stages go on in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the same thing happens all the time in the game.
Although the graphs are at the same level as in previous parts of the series, some tracks are pleasant to look at.
And yet the game doesn't give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, the autumn suburbs or high in snowy mountains are very pleasant.
Besides, the race occasionally revives an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you fall into a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under an avalanche.
Individual races are rather well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while, you're trying to outrun a few rivals (actually a conventional race); then you're trying to improve time (standard race with a stopwatch); or you're competing with one opponent.
Besides, from time to time, you run into the police, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of Jack's time escapes someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's nothing complicated.
While it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for the game, because it's not annoying; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more entertaining.
The racing model follows the tracks of previous models.
This means that it no longer represents anything special, but it cannot be considered a deficiency.
If you're looking for the simulation of real life, you're gonna have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although better options can be found in the market.
So far, so good.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't as good.
You don't expect a game like this to change and collide, but if you have no idea what your car's gonna do before you hit the target, something's wrong.
Usually, by overtaking or passing cars in a dense stream, you sometimes touch a different car slightly, and yet sometimes, in almost the same situation, your car starts spinning crazy.
Or crumbled.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
Restarts are designed so that if you break down or get away from the track, the game brings you back to the point where it's broken.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's good if something doesn't work out, but you can't rely entirely on it.
Sometimes restartings aren't enough, and you have to study a separate section of the race by heart.
The important weakness of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to go in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you come first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute later.
It's particularly annoying in situations where you see your rival easily passing between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you're in there, the cars are already positioned so that you either need to get around them or lose speed.
It doesn't matter when you're near them; it's arranged so that the situation always happens in front of your nose.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
This is especially obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's coming in front of you, he's making you look worse, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand trying to make the game more interesting and full of adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get annoying fast.
Too bad, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is exciting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter if you don't miss it - a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during racing is unusual.
You need to track the gas stations along the way, because they're the ones where your car can change, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports machines are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are suitable for direct highway sections; and exotic super-sport cars are suitable for technical driving, such as curved mountain roads.
===Story mode===The main mode mode is closely linked to the challenge mode regime; it is an individual race that you will learn from the course of the game.
Here you win for your personal business both medals and glasses common to the challenges and story regimes.
Many possibilities are available for higher levels of driving, ranging from machines to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the Autolog online function, which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players, and provides communication to the public.
Here's another drawback that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race to the sequence.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (we'll think so), where you run on the tracks in the dark (we'll think so).
Your speedometer shows numbers ranging from 150 to 200 km/h (to be assumed) when a subway train suddenly hits you from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, we've been discussing whether no one really thought for a second at the time of the game's creation, or whether its creators really think we're such fools.
The technical content of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression of the video game is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it is regrettable that at some critical points, the quality of the record is sometimes rather low.
This is especially true for accidents with a large number of participants where a good recording wouldn't help you either.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's on the amateur.
In order to please the widest possible youth audience, the soundtrack was "set up with different styles"; but it's unlikely that a lot of people buy a game because of its music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: Escape is pretty messy.
If the game were to avoid obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of incompleteness.
Of course, it's a good entertainment, but prepare to be blinded by shortcomings as a spotlight on the airport.
