IBM history: from raw knife to space missions.
==History==IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, and its original name, "Computation Corporation, Tabulation, Recording," was rather complex.
She took the name IBM in 1924 and originally called the brand, which was used for the company's Canadian and South American offices.
The future IBM was based on a merger of four companies, whose history began in the 1880s.
They owned technologies such as legendary "table watch," i.e. watches that record when staff members come and leave work.
The architect of the new company was Businessman Charles Runlet Flint, who until 1930 also headed the company's board of trustees.
Flint hired a competitor director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then moved IBM's founder into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of a solid corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as is clear from the name, began with the production and sale of various business equipment, ranging from raw knives and meat cutters to cashiers.
In the first four years of Watson's administration, the proceeds doubled to $9 million, and the company's vast expansion began on all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost 40 years later, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began developing artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM staff and computers helped NASA monitor space flights to Mercury, Saturn, and 1969, man flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family, the IBM line System/360.
A classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computers to Lenovo, a Chinese company, while buying PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus focusing entirely on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great progress with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make reasonable use of technologies in areas where this has not yet been planned and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in central and eastern Europe, IBM founded its office in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also runs a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters of central and eastern Europe is located in Prague, where there is also a world-class research group dedicated to speech recognition.
