Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourism agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies of the time were mostly selling tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, Czech tourists went on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which imposed considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to go by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; another individual journey was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but it was either necessary to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Foreign exchange permits were necessary for travel to the West and were not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations at home, resulting in a large number of cottages and summer houses, a habit that continues to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While prior to 1989 vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia today, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, marking the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough to travel to the West, everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (conserves, salami, etc.) in order to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a free convertible Czech kroner, after decades our tourists can finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income have been rising, leading to another important development around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has made it possible for travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, and air travel has now become incredibly cheap as compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually every developed world except the US, which made our travels even easier.
The next significant development in the history of post-revolutionary travel took place in 2000, with a strong demand leading to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will follow twelve exotic routes.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important development in this period, representing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. cancelled the visa requirement for Czech tourists, and our country has thus become a permanent member of the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during their leave abroad, including their expenses at destination.
