21st-century house in Vienna
The Pavilion in a New Place
Ingeborg Vissowski
The Austrian Pavilion for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, empty and abandoned.
Now it's being reopened as an exhibition center.
Austria's pavilion, designed by Karl Swanzer for the 1958 World Exposition in Brussels, is a well-known example of a modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, bold to express faith in technological progress.
Swanzer's pavilion won the Grand Prix in architecture in 1958 for his light floating steel and glass structure.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next World Exposition.
After all, he was famous for his legendary BMW four-cylinder tower and her sister, a cup-shaped building, in 1973.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna South Station, transformed and opened as the 20th Century Museum in 1962 - often referred to as the 20th Century House for this reason.
In any case, the building did not fit the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it did not have walls on which artwork could be hung and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna acquired a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001, and its condition has been getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has so far restored the pavilion, which was called the House of the 21st Century and will be used as a museum of modern art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday night - a joyous event in every sense.
Agnes Hussein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belveder Gallery in 2007, contributed to a new venture.
Hussein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a youth figure who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Modernist Museum in Salzburg, convinced politicians and guardians to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations, and decided how the building would be used.
The new museum was supposed to include a permanent exhibition of the Frits Wonruba Foundation, a cafe and bookstore, along with modern art, and an office building was to be built.
Strict Control & Limited Budget
Krishanitz was the perfect candidate for the project back then.
He was known, of course, thanks to the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession, Josef Olbrih, and won the competition, but he also studied with Swanzer at the University of Technology in Vienna, and the pavilion was "exceptionally important" for him, where he attended exhibitions "almost every week."
He knew the original design and the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its greatness and ease when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems encountered during the last restructuring were much more serious, the building was an "energy absorber," says Krishanitz.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, the glass fibre-enhanced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced by a high-strength safety glass.
The thermal bridge was reinforced or replaced and asbestos removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors created space for a new use of the building, a falling light well between the building and the street providing lighting - a virtually new building, but still the elegant pavilion of Swanzer.
The original outer doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red brown colour of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
It's all under strict control of the museum department and with a limited budget.
"We often had to find material that was good, cheap, and approved by the museum department," says Krishanitz, pointing out that it was uneven in the basement.
The building remained flexible and easy, despite constraints, challenges and transformations.
Krishanitz recently noticed that the pavilion "from Brussels" was a rude - typical story of "drips in the city."
Such an architecture is "always out of place" and nevertheless wants to "stimulate real awareness."
The 21st-century house is in a very right place, because the city's planning has had unexpected success, and a completely rebuilt "main station" block with offices and real estate grows around the Swiss garden.
The 21st century house could be supplemented by the second building of Krishanitz, the French collector von Habsburg, who purchased the Berlin Temporary Exhibition Hall and reportedly negotiates with the city about its location next door in the Swiss Garden.
