Peter Englund's tense and very kind new book, "The Beauty and Grief: The Personal History of World War I," begins with a long list of actors from which the heart freezes.
Here's a tip on how to read: carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You'll get to know these people very close as Mr. Anglund tells you, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon at moments when, like one of these men and women, you'll get lost and lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, who awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's written right now is unusual, he describes it quite accurately as "anti-history work."
There are few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, slender journalists or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, how much "book about what it looked like," it's about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and the state of the spirit."
The book "Beauty and Grievance" brought together the experiences of 20 more or less unmarked men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people are gonna be heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses his arm or leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are shimmering here like church candles: new ones are added to a multitude of others, and some will be extinguished at that time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the historical book standard.
This is also an amendment to the notion that World War I was only a severe, extensive war on the West Front.
"Beauty and Grievance" ably gives the panorama of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under pyramids; the unsolved problem is tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people as a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smokeless powder.
When there's a canonnade nearby, and you're a woman and you're at home with the kids, will you stay or run?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on and why we have to fight this war.
"Deficiencies," Mr. Englund notes, "recovered by conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessive ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and Grief" tracks the fate of people like Florence Farmboro, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas Flot.
Their stories are mainly taken from memoirs, letters, and other materials already published.
The stories about their lives may be scary or exciting, but they are extremely alive thanks to Mr. Englund ' s small moments and partial details.
Many of them are about deprivations and how to deal with them.
When he tells the story of a German schoolgirl, he says, "Erzac, everywhere is an erzaz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminium, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues to talk about erzazz food in Germany.
He describes "measles of pressured rice welded in ovine fat (and decorated with a false bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skin; shoes covered with wood."
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes authorized for the production of sausage, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories speak of honor and courage.
One American observes the most violent tendency and says about war: "You feel that, after all, it's what men were created for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, a evening newspaper or a bestseller, and to claim that this display is civilization and that under your cufflinked shirt there's no barbarous hiding underneath."
On the contrary, the British soldier observes that he is likely to die and that no one will notice or grieve.
"When a man accepts the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think it would happen in front of the public," he writes.
But it's the other way around, it's scary like a convicted man being hanged in secret.
Other comments concern old Europe, which is falling apart, and new forms of fear.
"The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition," says Mr. Englund, "war factories."
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new view of the ingenuity of the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressed and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-stained suit that makes a massacre at the desk."
People act in an unexpected way: low-level actions are as much as heroics.
Mr. Englund described soldiers who had tried hard to catch a sexually transmitted disease from prostitutes in order to avoid service on the front.
