The walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was an ordinary guy who shared his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Bravik, who confessed to the massacre in Norway in July, which claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Bravik could act alone, he was far from being alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing for his computer attack, interacting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized it was easy to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism at the British DEMOS Research Centre.
The availability of personal data on Facebook is so high, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the website's advertising tool to identify the necessary demographic group with scientific precision - what marketologists have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then planted an ad for them, but instead of showing a new band or a diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that included questions about their level of education, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
With Facebook's help, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview over 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without even leaving the office.
"This is a completely new way to do research," Bartlett says.
Some results are less striking: online right-wing groups - most often male youth, who are unhappy with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor."
DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything in the world, ranging from health issues to social trends expressed in "Likes," posts on the wall and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three entries a day, Facebook's "super-relevant information" causes a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook's beauty is that it allows you to study people you can't approach on the street with a notebook.
"If you wanted to interview people from the British National Party earlier, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to join the party, and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all of this-- you're addressing them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of Wisconsin University, Madison, and her colleagues revealed that students who discussed their drunken performances on Facebook were significantly more likely to be at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunken statuses.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," reported Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Conduct and Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who wouldn't otherwise be found."
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The website's data processing team processed statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout mid-term in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mainly using information they have access to only - the champions of cyberfreedom have long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site watches them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become participants in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined rules for conducting offline research, online data are publicly available.
"I don't think many users have at least thought about what an researcher can observe their profiles," says Neil Selwin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using the students' public Facebook pages.
"How they imagined it was just between them and their friends."
The question then arises as to the methodology.
There's no guarantee even offline that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user's page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two totally different things," Selwin says.
That is why, despite the years of its work in technology research, Selwin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools available for use.
"Nothing can replace getting into the real world and communicating with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline."
