It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This film, slightly edited, became the basis for a 68-minute film by Steve Jobs: Lost Interview, released on Landmark Theatres on Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for hating a detailed interview, Jobs seems to be unusable here to present his technological philosophy and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points in the interview, there are long intervals between questions and answers - reflections of 10 to 15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be precise.
There are also moments where Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems annoyed by Kringley's questions, which make him move faster to issues or events of greater importance.
In the Picsar era, the iPods and iPhones of the Lost Interview, there is something sinisterly prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies are doing right and wrong and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about the postmortem assessments of Jobs' work, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring in Jobs that we see here, a disturbing dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
