How to catch a lie
A quick look at the last headlines shows how serious and widespread deception and lies are in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman Kane is busy challenging allegations of sexual harassment from several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The administration of the University of Pennsylvania was charged with perjury because they allegedly concealed that the retired football coach had raped the boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught when, with the microphone on, he told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lying destroys careers and shakes countries.
Congressman New York and Internet inhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his delusions, which were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with financial fraud during a campaign to conceal extramarital ties.
Again, no one who lived at that time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton found lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Levinski during his second term in office.
The history of fraud in school and college exams is common.
There have been instances in which teachers have given students answers to tests in order to have a good evaluation of their performance.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Within one day, research shows that you can be lied 10 to 200 times.
It is now assumed that much of this is a lie to salvation.
Another study revealed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Identifying lies or proving lies is a skill that everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike the room game, which is like, say, charades, where you have to say, "Gone!" the detection of lies is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most old myths about lies have been cleared.
Liars look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush, or fuss.
There is no reason to conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
An experienced unveiler of lies can reach the truth by observing the structure of the allegations, the mimics, the structure of the questions, and the temporal characteristics.
I have spent several years exploring scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of the knowledge of lies, and it is clear that the detection of lies is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps guide our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel free to control their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, whereas women lie about others, usually to protect someone ' s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried (but the lies they say are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a fraud, others will feel less guilty by deceiving you.
How do you know if anyone's lying?
First of all, watch your target's normal behavior.
It's called "defining the original state."
This helps to provide a starting point for measuring changes further.
Observe the position, the laughter, the vocal characteristics of your object.
Well, it would be good to know if a man is always kicking his feet in normal condition, then you will not be making unfair accusations when you see a footbump in the middle of a meeting.
Next, search for groups of deceiving notes verbales and non-verbal actions.
Think of these groups as red flags, not as proof of deception.
Liars can record the upper part of their body when they try to remember their story, they can set their feet towards the door, lean towards the door, change their position in a certain way, or show "facilitation after interview" -- a exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all complex questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-interrogation signal to just look at this relief after the interview.
So, look at your object's speech.
It is known that Scott Patterson has erred and used the past time to claim that his murdered wife is alive, leading to her search throughout the country.
Perpetrators can also use distance in their speech: "I did not have sexual relations with this woman... Miss Levinski" or repeat the complex question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely understandable.
Someone can use "qualification language" when they answer a difficult question: "Well... the truth is... as far as I know... as far as I know."
This makes the answer emotional rather than factual, and is often a red flag.
There's no magical means to detect lies, but it's possible to master the skill of detection.
These skills will increase everyone's chances of not falling victim to skilled crooks in their professional and private lives.
