Climate issues slowed the economy
During the first year of the reign of Mario López, unemployment and the illegal labour market rose in Sinaloa, foreign financing declined and the economy weakened.
The year 2011 - which will enter the economic history of Sinaloa as the first year of the government of Mario López Valdes - is also called the year of change, which has given rise to great hopes for economic development, but, given the unfavourable climatic conditions of the beginning of the year, there has been no growth, but there has been a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February not only resulted in millions of losses for the agricultural sector, but they limited the growth potential of the public economy, causing a 3.6 per cent decline in overall economic activity in the first half of the year, largely due to the historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to a report on areas affected by frost provided by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 per cent were affected in their entirety and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially affected, with vegetables, maize and naut being the main crops damaged.
The decline in economic activity led to a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters, an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, between January and March 55,053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, increased to 5.28% in the second quarter, and continued to rise to 6.19 per cent between July and September, a proportion equivalent to more than 74,000 unemployed Sinaloa residents, an increase of 18,969 from the first half.
Liquidity reduction
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year has been dominated by many factors, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the increase in unemployment can be attributed indirectly to actions taken in public policy.
"What we see now is an increase in unemployment, which is linked to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market to limit the resources imposed by the law passed in Congress to combat money-laundering, because it is difficult for people who illegally own dollars to work with, invest and use them in something," he said.
Stopped immigration
López Cervantes said that there was a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state to seek work abroad has been limited in the U.S., primarily due to entry difficulties, and in the latter, because once they enter, they already face very many difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stays and requires jobs here in the state as a result of rising unemployment," he said.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of Sinaloa ' s labour market is worse, given the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and malfeasance, another reminder of State employment is provided by low wages; the State has the lowest wages in the country, as recorded by the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers until September was 5,352 pesos, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reducing FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high unemployment rate, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, between January and July the state had $630,697 FDI, a decline of 87.74 per cent compared with $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
