The Court will approve the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (HJ) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which postpones the so-called "transfer to digital television" from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not obtained to cancel it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his mandate by issuing a decree detailing the actions to be taken in the transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, constitutional claims filed by the Senate were rejected because of the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains valid.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right established by law by the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned therein regarding the introduction of digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a debate on the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules of the measure to be prepared by the public administration.
"I also do not believe that it would affect the autonomy of the regulator" and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas, such as telecommunications, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the governance of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals - one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years - has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean delaying the benefits of digitization, which included meeting public needs, which had not only a technical dimension, "as it covered economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he said, "require the work of the whole system, which is founded on the principle of public economic administration, and includes a group of authorities which the Constitution unites in the executive branch of the State."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting and had done so through the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any event affects the competence of Congress, enforces the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly in the administrative sphere, he said.
In Michoacán, the ability to count "votes for voice" is being analysed.
According to data transmitted to the APPR, the difference between the first and second seats in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 minutes.
The possibility of counting "votes for the vote" is real with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where, according to data from the Provisional Electoral Results Programme, the difference between the first and second seats in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 records.
In this light, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IMI), Maria de Los Angeles Lyanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral corps adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not adopt the State Constitution or Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, as the State Congress approved reforms shortly before their legal entry into force in the electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time frame specified in the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJ) ruled on the constitutional claim submitted by the local legislature and declared the state representative's vote on constitutional reform to be "unauthorized and illegal," as he did not have the right to "permit or support them."
In an interview about the possibility of a "vote for voice" by Maria de los Angeles Lyanderal, she argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of the IMS, it would be possible to present a partial or full counting of votes by the local electoral authority.
Thus, a partial count of one or more ballot boxes may be made under conditions that: the results of the records do not match; there is no record of voting and counting in the ballot box or is not available to the chairman; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, the total counting of votes in all ballot boxes in the elections may occur when there is a indication that the difference between the proposed winner candidate and those who won the second ballot is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the party representative and/or the coalition that nominated the second candidate.
A total count of votes will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is determined that the difference between the winner and the second-ranking candidate is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a petition from a political party whose candidate has taken second place, in the event that the ballot boxes, which were counted in part, are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case for the elections in Morelia, where, according to the UDPR, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16%, not even counting 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocols.
