Muhica will meet next Wednesday with her Mexican colleague, Felipe Calderón, the most important point in the extensive schedule of meetings with political, commercial authorities and the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to a schedule published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two Presidents in Guadalajara would be "friendly for the exchange of information on political relations between the two nations," as the South American leadership had published on its website.
According to local media, Muhica is seeking support from Calderón for Uruguay in an incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannet.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remained tax havens, a statement that prompted Uruguay ' s protest and withdrawal for consultation by his ambassador in a European country.
Mexico has been chairing, since November, G20, a group composed of the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, had an agreement with South American countries since January this year on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Government of Uruguay has tried in recent years to expedite the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to leave this "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, drawn from countries that do not benefit from international standards of tax cooperation.
With regard to the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
