Meanwhile, Gilberto López Meyer, Director-General of Airports and Support Services, said that during the attack, a presidential helicopter was driving at cruise speed and that it had occurred on soft, rising soil.
"This information reinforces the hypothesis of a normal flight manoeuvre at the moment of impact," he said.
At a press conference, the owner of SCT, Pérez Hacomé, listed six important elements of the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aviation regulations, the flight was performed by visual flight rules, which means that the crew must be visible during flight and landing.
Weather conditions:
The AICM reports identified suitable conditions for take-off when the aircraft headed to the border between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, where layers of clouds were observed at low altitudes.
Routes selected:
It is possible that due to cloud conditions, the team was searching for a lower height and greater visibility in the Quernavaca Valley.
Place of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording from the radar of the aircraft are likely to be consistent before the impact with no loss of control or change of direction.
Broken debris in a small area:
The information available to date indicates that the front and the side lines were hit.
The fragmentation of the debris makes it clear that the helicopter encountered the ground in an environment of structural integrity.
There were no obvious signs of fire or explosion:
In the area of disaster, undetected evidence remains in the wreckage of the vessel, some kind of explosion or fire.
Recent studies have shown that there may have been multiple contact with land.
During the field work, pieces of aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, with a slope of seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The pictures show the sequence in which it was destroyed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had several collisions with the ground.
After careful study, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found in more territory than the designated area near the site of the disaster, thus reinforcing the assumption that the impact occurred in a structurally integrated environment.
MSS announces an obese gene search program
Social protection leads research on obesity genes in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Social Protection Institute (MSSI) announced that it was conducting a study to detect obesity genes in children and young people, known as the "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Teenage" protocol, which would provide a calculation of signs of overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Centre for the Twenty-first Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is assisted by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Centre for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invites the population (written or not) to participate in MSSI sports centres participating in the study to the Mexico Valley, where tests with children will be conducted from 8 a.m. every Saturday.
He stressed that the protocol had been launched at the Kuautemoke Sports Centre (west of the State of Mexico) and that since 8 October, the events had been held at the Nessaualkoyotl Sports Centre (east of the State of Mexico).
Once the target of 500 to 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (northern Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors among children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated and the main objective will be to bring together 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 with the permission of parents and under their supervision to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that anthropometric measurements would be made on Saturday for all participants (weight, height and waist), blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in weight among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there has been an increase in just six years: in the case of boys, 77 per cent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 per cent; in the case of overweight, there has also been a significant increase," a MSSI specialist said.
He said that the rationale for finding markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans were 65 per cent descendants of American Indians, 30 per cent descendants of Europeans and 5 per cent descendants of Africans, a condition that affected genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main result of obesity genetics is the body ' s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is delayed in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (s) and forearms means the probability of metabolism or even prediabetism.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, and the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and changes in lifestyle that must be made to avoid illness.
Cruz López explained that there were three main causes that caused overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentary lifestyles, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of television and using transportation at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie consumption, i.e. increased consumption of sweet beverage and carbs (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition analysed in the program.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Department, developed a polymer-modified batum to produce a mixture of best quality, environmentally and temperature resistant.
If the signals sent by the road surface were to be addressed, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 yams for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of the asphalt road surface is normal, the number of pits may be reduced or reduced to zero.
His lecture on the technology view of the pits of the International Year of Chemistry reported that the laboratory for which he was responsible was developing a polymer-modified batum to produce a mixture of characteristics close to the bitumen, but with the best resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some towns in the north, to improve road quality and thus to resist the formation of pits.
He explained that the bitumen, the heaviest part of the oil, was the sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some were the high molecular mass called asphaltens, and others were the low molecular mass called the Maltese, which together gave road cover to its characteristic viscosity.
The viscosity of the bitumen is the fact that he behaves like a liquid at about 180 degrees at high temperatures, his viscosity is very high at 120 degrees Celsius, and at 50 degrees Celsius he retains almost a solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not permanent, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, as said by a chemical engineer.
The chimphaka noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the highest layers is a bitumen made of small stones, which are dropped into a bitumen and then crushed.
Every stone that makes this coating, he said, is buried in a bitumen.
When vehicles are moved and forces are applied, this helps the force to be very well distributed on the road.
If it was a modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, the last layer, called the obsolescence layer, which is made of a small stone, actually sand, also submerged in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these forces, the deterioration layer also requires appropriate thickness and the material from which it is manufactured must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it significantly affected asphalt.
When the earth is wet, the water enters the surface and it is difficult to get out of it, it causes the softening of all layers of the surface and thus the formation of the pits.
When the pits were formed, he said, the first layer of wear was worn out and only then it affected the bitumen, but the damage did not occur instantaneously, a process that should be taken into account in the first signs of ongoing repair programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of the surface must always be related to the transport load and must be guaranteed to ensure that this requirement is met in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Raphael Herrera said that there is still much to learn about the bitumen and, for example, bitumen emulsions that in other countries are already on the market and even helping to fix pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
